@angular/compiler-cli

### Description

When using Angular's new control flow syntax (`@switch`  `@case`  `@default` ), the compiler does not warn or error if there are duplicate `@case` conditions.
This can lead to unexpected behavior because the next  `@case` is shadowed or ignored without the developer realizing it.

```html
@switch (staticText) {
  @case ('pending') {
    Pending First
  }
  @case ('pending') {
    Duplicate
  }
  @default {
    Other default switch case
  }
}

```
Expected: Compiler should produce a diagnostic warning or error about the duplicate 'pending' case.
Actual: No warning is shown; only the first branch is effective, but the duplicate `@case` silently fails.



More cases

```html
@switch (someObject) {
  @case ({}) {
    Pending Object
  }
  @case ('pending') {
    Duplicate
  }
  @default {
    Other default switch case
  }
}

```
Why this is a problem

Developers may believe both cases are valid, but only one is actually respected.

This creates silent, hard-to-detect bugs.




### Proposed solution

Add a compiler diagnostic (warning or error) when duplicate `@case` expressions are detected within the same `@switch` block.

I could work on proposing a PR.

### Alternatives considered

Let them remember how `@switch` works according to the documentation API, but including me as a user, I don't read it completely.

https://angular.dev/guide/templates/control-flow#conditionally-display-content-with-the-switch-block

